Shader-Based Renewable Energy Farm Visualization
Name: Gunabhiram Aruru
Course: CSCI 4229/5229 Computer Graphics

Current Project Description
---------------------------
This program develops the working prior renewable-energy farm scene into the
final-project codebase. It preserves the handmade textured scene, moving
positional light, animation, navigation, and object inspection while adding
renewable-energy structures and restrained secondary scenery.

The main graduate contribution is a GLSL-animated wind-flow visualization
coupled to the physical turbine animation. The shared wind speed controls all
three turbine rotors and the travel rate of translucent airflow ribbons, with
the original blade speed preserved at the default wind speed of 1.0.

The current scene contains:
- three handmade animated wind turbines
- a handmade barn/shed
- a handmade framed greenhouse with separately drawn glazing
- a handmade four-panel solar array with support posts
- four low-poly handmade trees
- a fence and path
- a textured ground plane
- a visible moving positional light
- twelve translucent wind-flow ribbons crossing the turbine field

The greenhouse has transparent blue-green wall and roof glass rendered with
fixed-pipeline OpenGL alpha blending. The frame and all other opaque scene
objects are drawn first. The glass is drawn last with depth testing still
enabled but depth writes temporarily disabled, so objects behind the glass
remain visible without the glass breaking normal hidden-surface removal.
The wind ribbons use wind.vert and wind.frag for animated displacement and
air-flow coloring. Fog will be implemented in a later phase.

Build Instructions
------------------
Run these commands from this directory.

On Linux or macOS:
    make clean
    make

The Makefile compiles with:
    g++ -std=c++11 -Wall -Wextra

GLEW is optional rather than required. On Linux systems configured to use it:
    make USEGLEW=1

Run Instructions
----------------
    ./final

The files wind.vert and wind.frag must remain in the project directory when
the program runs.

Controls
--------
0                 Inspect the full scene
1                 Inspect turbines only
2                 Inspect barn/farmhouse only
3                 Inspect greenhouse only
4                 Inspect solar-panel array only
5                 Inspect fence and secondary objects
Arrow keys        Rotate overview camera or navigate in first-person mode
PageUp/PageDown   Adjust zoom or field of view
+ or =            Zoom in / decrease field of view
- or _            Zoom out / increase field of view
m                 Cycle orthographic, perspective, and first-person modes
R                 Reset to the default full-scene perspective camera
r                 Pause/resume turbine blade rotation
a                 Toggle axes
l                 Toggle lighting
t                 Toggle textures
g                 Toggle greenhouse glass visibility
S                 Toggle shader-based wind flow/ribbons
Space             Pause/resume automatic light movement
, and .           Move the light angle manually
[ and ]           Decrease/increase wind speed
< and >           Lower/raise the light
q or ESC          Exit

Default State
-------------
The program starts in a perspective overview with lighting, textures, depth
testing, moving light, and turbine animation enabled.
Greenhouse glass is visible and transparent by default.
Wind speed starts at 1.0 and can be adjusted from 0.0 through 5.0.
The wind flow is visible by default. Its shader is enabled when it compiles and
links successfully.
If GLSL is unsupported or either shader file fails to load, compile, or link,
the program reports the error and continues with fixed-pipeline fallback
ribbons.

Code Reuse and Project Phases
-----------------------------
The handmade turbine, barn, fence, path, ground, BMP loader, lighting,
texture mapping, navigation, and animation are reused from the author's
prior course project.

Phase 1 changes include:
- final-project source, executable, title, and documentation naming
- perspective overview as the initial camera
- object inspection modes 0 through 5
- centered camera presets for each inspection group
- scene drawing refactored into named object-group functions
- updated HUD showing project, camera, inspection, lighting, and texture state

Current object additions include:
- greenhouse frame, roof structure, and separately rendered glass panels
- angled photovoltaic panels with handmade supports and specular material
- low-poly trees with handmade trunks and cone canopies

Phase 2 transparency changes include:
- opaque greenhouse frame/base rendering separated from glass rendering
- all opaque objects rendered before the transparent glass pass
- standard source-alpha blending for wall and roof glass
- depth testing retained while glass depth writes are temporarily disabled
- depth writes restored and blending disabled immediately after drawing glass
- g/G glass visibility toggle and HUD glass-state display

Phase 3 wind-speed changes include:
- shared wind speed for all turbines, clamped from 0.0 through 5.0
- frame-rate-independent blade animation based on elapsed wall-clock time
- linear blade-speed formula: 45 degrees/second multiplied by wind speed
- default wind speed 1.0 retains the prior 45 degrees/second, or 7.5 RPM
- [ and ] wind-speed controls and remapped < and > light-height controls
- HUD display of wind speed, turbine RPM, and blade pause state

Phase 4 shader infrastructure includes:
- portable text-file loading, shader compilation, and program linking
- compile and link error logs with non-fatal shader-off fallback
- wind.vert and wind.frag with time and windSpeed uniforms
- optional USEGLEW build support without an unconditional GLEW dependency
- GL_GLEXT_PROTOTYPES on non-Apple builds that do not use GLEW
- S shader toggle and HUD loaded/failed status
- fixed-pipeline scene rendering remained unchanged before Phase 5 ribbons

Phase 5 wind-flow contribution includes:
- twelve handmade GL_QUAD_STRIP airflow ribbons passing through the farm
- vertex-shader sine displacement driven by time and windSpeed uniforms
- fragment-shader blue/white coloring with animated translucent alpha
- shared windSpeed coupling ribbon travel speed to turbine blade RPM
- ribbons rendered after opaque geometry with depth writes disabled
- greenhouse glass rendered after ribbons for controlled transparency layering
- S wind-flow toggle and HUD Shader/Wind Flow status
- fixed-pipeline translucent ribbon fallback when shader loading fails

No fog is included yet.

Textures
--------
Only textures currently used by the program are included:
- textures/grass.bmp
- textures/metal.bmp
- textures/path.bmp
- textures/roof.bmp
- textures/wood.bmp

Known Limitations
-----------------
- Greenhouse glass uses fixed-pipeline blending; no GLSL effects are applied.
- Texture and shader paths are relative, so run ./final from the project
  directory.
